status_message_cleaned: It’s Arctic Science Month! This past summer, an underwater cable system was laid in part of the Northwest Passage to help scientists measure ice thickness, water temperature, passive acoustics & much more. The -km cable connects to an on-shore computer that communicates directly to the Bedford Institute of Oceanography in Dartmouth, Nova Scotia. This system helps to collect important data in real-time, even when the ice is m thick!

status_message_cleaned: Have you ever wondered where the salmon in British Columbia’s hatcheries come from? First, we capture adult salmon to collect their milt and eggs, which are mixed together to fertilize and then placed in an aquarium to incubate. Once the eggs have hatched, the young salmon are fed in rearing ponds until they’re ready to be released into local streams. These practices allow our hatcheries to follow the natural life cycle of salmon while they work to improve low salmon stocks. Learn more about the Pacific salmon life-cycle here:

status_message_cleaned: The Tubenose Goby is a small, bottom-dwelling invasive fish that lives among the aquatic vegetation found in nearshore waters of lakes and rivers. Since its discovery in North America in the late s, Tubenose Goby have been found in a few locations in the Great Lakes. To prevent the spread of this invasive species, never buy or use Tubenose Goby as bait, and never transfer live bait between waterbodies. It is against the law. Scientists are concerned about the possible long-term effects, because it can beat resident fish for habitat and food. This is a real concern for bottom-dwelling fishes, like Rainbow Darter and Northern Madtom. For more information, or to report sightings, please visit

status_message_cleaned: Our scientists in Newfoundland and Labrador are improving the accuracy of weather and climate forecasts for all Canadians through important contributions to ocean forecasting systems. Over the past two years, researchers like Fraser Davidson have deployed oceanographic ‘drifters’ to collect hourly data on temperature and air pressure on the Newfoundland and Labrador Shelves. This data allows us to work with Environment and Climate Change Canada to evaluate and improve marine weather forecasting systems. status_message_cleaned: The Round Goby is a small, bottom-dwelling invasive fish that has unfortunately spread through all five Great Lakes in less than a decade. To prevent the spread of this invasive species, never buy or use Round Goby as bait, and never live transfer bait between waterbodies, which are against the law. They prefer waters with rocky and sandy bottoms, and feed aggressively on insects, molluscs, and other small organisms. They have even been known to eat juvenile freshwater mussels, many of which are at-risk! Round Goby are also found in some inland waters in southern Ontario such as Lake Simcoe, the Trent River, Rice Lake, and parts of the Otonabee River. To report sightings, please visit 2

status_message_cleaned: Help protect our oceans! We work hard to keep Canada’s waters and coasts safe and clean through programs and initiatives like the Oceans Protection Plan and Coastal Restoration Fund. But we can’t do it alone. To encourage the public to get involved, we visit communities with educational materials and take part in school visits and beach clean-ups. Unfortunately, the waters around many Canadian harbours aren’t as clean as they could be. Recently, our researchers from Newfoundland and Labrador, Corey Morris & Dan Porter, presented results from a survey of harbours over years. During scientific dives, they uneectedly found, and videotaped, lots of garbage – everything from carpet, rubber gloves, rubber boots to appliances like BBQs, stove, even a washer with laundry still inside. Everyone has a role in protecting the ocean and the creatures that live there. Reduce the garbage going into the ocean by recycling, reusing and refusing plastic where you can.

status_message_cleaned: For the past two years, our team of Quebec biologists has been collecting data on artificial reefs developed for American lobster in the Magdalen Islands and the Gaspé Peninsula. These m by m reefs are composed mainly of rocks of different sizes. They serve to offset the serious harm caused by marine environment projects by providing shelter and food for lobsters of all sizes. They become true nurseries for these crustaceans and are also, according to what the dives on the sites have shown, colonized by a wide variety of organisms. Biologists now better understand the benefits of these developments to the surrounding environment and can make recommendations to developers to increase the stability of development over the longer term. status_message_cleaned: Canada's first marine biological research station began operations in St. Andrews, New Brunswick in . Built aboard a floating raft, the station was very small and resembled a Pullman railway car. After moving around Canada for several years, the Biological Board of Canada decided that a permanent biological station was needed on the Atlantic coast. St. Andrews was chosen because of the diverse biological and physical environment in Passamaquoddy Bay and the Bay of Fundy and its proximity to important commercial fisheries for herring, groundfish and invertebrate species. status_message_cleaned: Northern Snakehead is an invasive species that has not yet been found in any of Canada’s aquatic ecosystems, but we want to be on the lookout! Most snakehead species are native to warmer regions, but the Northern Snakehead occurs naturally in colder waters. Northern Snakehead can eat practically any small animal or fish they encounter. They can travel across land and live out of water for at least three days and reproduce quickly. If they find a way into natural freshwater ecosystems, they have the potential to cause serious damage to recreational and commercial fisheries. Report sightings:

status_message_cleaned: We are taking concrete action to protect the endangered North Atlantic Right Whale for future generations. We will be working with partners on a comprehensive approach which includes specific proposals like seasonal speed restrictions to avoid collisions, adjusting fishing gear and testing new gear to reduce the risk of whale entanglements, and working to reduce lost fishing gear in our waters. These strategies were discussed at a roundtable with eerts, scientists, Indigenous peoples and representatives from fishing organizations and marine transportation industries in Moncton, New Brunswick yesterday. In addition to the speed restrictions and increased surveillance implemented this past summer, these actions will help us better protect this iconic species.

status_message_cleaned: The Quagga Mussel is an Aquatic Invasive Species closely related to the invasive Zebra Mussel. The Quagga mussel is found in the southern Great Lakes (lakes Ontario, Michigan, Huron and Erie). Although they have already invaded parts of Ontario, other provinces, like Alberta, Manitoba, and Saskatchewan are working to prevent them from establishing there. If you think you’ve seen or caught a Quagga Mussel: * Do not release it into the water. * Collect it and keep it frozen. If you can’t do that, destroy it. * Note the location (with GPS coordinates if possible) as well as the observation date. * Contact Fisheries and Oceans Canada Click here for more information about this Aquatic Invasive Species:

status_message_cleaned: Learn to identify invasive species! Silver Carp is one of four species of invasive Asian carp and is best known for its startled response. You’ve probably seen videos of them leaping as high as three metres above the water’s surface when disturbed by boat motors or other noise. Silver Carp have a large, scaleless head, and a toothless mouth without barbels. Closely related to Bighead Carp, Silver Carp tends to be narrower in shape. They are greyish-black on top and have small, curved scales. They can live up to years! If you think you’ve found a Silver Carp, put it on ice (do not freeze) and contact the Invading Species Hotline at: -800-563-7711 (in Ontario), or visit cU

Their scales are large with dark edges, and their fins are clear to grey-brown. Adult Grass Carp mostly eat aquatic vegetation. They can clog intake structures in power stations and water treatment plants and cause millions of dollars in damages. Zebra Mussels are found throughout all the Great Lakes. They are an average of -2.5 cm, reaching up to cm long, triangular in shape, and are black or brown with white to yellow zigzagged patterns. If you think you’ve seen or caught a Zebra Mussel where they are not known to occur: *Do not release it into the water. *Catch it and keep it frozen. status_message_cleaned: This summer, our scientists returned to Canada’s Arctic Beaufort Sea to learn more about the diverse species that live there. status_message_cleaned: Our scientists dove two kilometers deep to study previously unelored underwater mountains off the coast of Vancouver Island: the Union and Dellwood Seamounts. We used a camera to elore these two extinct volcanoes and the biodiversity hotspots they support. This research will offer insight into their ecological importance and inform how we might better conserve this potential Marine Protect Area. Take a look at what we discovered and celebrate this unique marine habitat.

status_message_cleaned: The ecosystem research team in Tremblay Sound, Nunavut, came across a bird colony! A glaucous gull colony of approximately couples was found on a cliff at the far south of the strait. These birds can nest in different habitats, like cliffs and wetlands. As a result, they have a broad diet. Remains of fish of different sizes and even lemming bones were found, providing a picture of their diet. The cliff offers gull eggs and young birds protection against predators and excellent access to marine resources.

status_message_cleaned: The Marine Institute is the first to receive close to $4.7 million to restore eelgrass beds and marine life habitat through the development of artificial reefs. This will help restore migratory corridors for Atlantic salmon and increase ecosystem productivity to support Species At Risk such as the Blue whale and Leatherback sea turtles. This project will benefit this entire ecosystem in Placentia Bay, Newfoundland and Labrador. Congratulations to the Marine Institute! We look forward to our partnership and the good work that lies ahead. The $75 Million Coastal Restoration Fund, part of Canada’s Oceans Protection Plan, supports projects that help to restore coastal aquatic habitats.

status_message_cleaned: Arctic sculpins live in deep and shallow waters where they eat small crustaceans, other small fish and fish larvae. They can tolerate water as cold as °C. In order to survive these extreme conditions, they developed a special antifreeze protein to prevent their blood from freezing solid. Sculpins may be a predicator of changes at the bottom of the food web. We collected individuals from two species of sculpins, as part of the ecosystem research project in Tremblay Sound, Nunavut, to better understand their feeding habits, as well as the role they play in the ecosystem.

status_message_cleaned: Greenland sharks are the only sharks that can tolerate the cold Arctic waters. Most Greenland sharks have a parasite, Ommatokoita elongate, that attaches to their eyes, destroys the tissues, and causes partial to complete blindness. The Greenland shark lives in deep water where there is rarely light, so they mainly use their other senses to get around. We have been tagging Greenland sharks as part of the Tremblay Ecosystem Approach project in Nunavut to track their movement and determine their role in the food web.

Bowheads can weigh between to tons, reach a length of m, and live up to years; yet, can still manage to launch their massive bodies out of the water! Wow! Bowheads filter water through baleen by straining the surface of the water to capture zooplankton, which plays a major role in the ecosystem. Researchers hope to determine from food web studies if the whales come for the food, or perhaps simply for a summer break.

The Atlantic walrus prefers cold waters and there may still be up to several thousand walruses in Canadian waters.

status_message_cleaned: Shark sightings and accidental interactions are common in Newfoundland and Labrador waters and the public plays a vital role in shark research. If you see a shark, dead or alive, take a photo. Note the date and location and send it to Carolyn.Miri-mpo.gc.ca. But do it safely. No shark selfies! Don’t bring the shark aboard your boat. Its skin is like sandpaper and the edges of the fins are as sharp as filleting knives. Wear heavy gloves and use bolt cutters to snap off the hook and line.

status_message_cleaned: Many of the leatherback sea turtles seen in our waters nest in Trinidad and Tobago. Every year, our Sea Turtle Biologist Mike James travels there to work with local conservation groups to collect data from nesting leatherback sea turtles. His work enables remote detecting of turtles on the beach so research can be done throughout the nesting season. Last week, his Trinidad and Tobago colleagues joined him in Halifax to discuss how they can further this collaboration and observe research activities underway off Nova Scotia.

status_message_cleaned: British Columbia’s Fraser River salmon returns are low this year and conservation is our first priority. After conservation, Indigenous groups have priority access to fish for food, social, and ceremonial uses. One of the keys to protecting the future of salmon stocks is effective monitoring and enforcement to detect and deter illegal fishing activity by all user groups. Our Fishery Officers are actively monitoring and enforcing all fishing activity using a variety of methods, including aerial, ocean, river, on-the-ground, night and undercover patrols. status_message_cleaned: Located in the eastern Gaspé Peninsula in Quebec, the American Bank was selected in as a potential site for a new Marine Protected Area. In-depth knowledge of the site is an essential prerequisite for creating a Marine Protected Area. We know the site has many assets: diversity of its habitats; presence of many commercially valuable species and species at risk; as well as significant potential as a feeding ground for various species of fish and marine mammals. The establishment of the American Bank as a Marine Protected Area should promote the productivity and diversity of commercially fished species as well as the recovery of species at risk.

status_message_cleaned: Effective immediately, vessels travelling in the western Gulf of St. Lawrence are mandated to reduce their speed to a maximum of knots. The Government of Canada implemented the temporary mandatory slow-down for vessels longer than metres in an effort to minimize risks to right whales in the area. Following the recent whale deaths in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, we are making every effort possible to prevent further incidents and continue to work on the recovery of the species. We are awaiting results from the necropsies, and we have closed snow crab fishing to prevent entanglements. Other fixed gear fisheries such as rock and toad crab fisheries have either been restricted to fish in shallow water or have had a delayed opening. For more information on our actions to date: Transport and Infrastructure in Canada

status_message_cleaned: We are taking action on the recovery, protection and conservation of the endangered North Atlantic Right Whale. The deaths of the whales in the Gulf of St. Lawrence this summer is an unprecedented situation. We are conducting necropsies on the deceased whales with partners to learn the cause of death and determine next steps. We closed some snow crab fisheries early and other fixed gear fisheries have either been restricted or have been delayed. We have notified fishermen to stay on high alert and report any sightings. We are regularly conducting surveillance flights to monitor for whales. The Canadian Coast Guard is asking shipping vessels entering our waters to decrease their speed until further notice. status_message_cleaned: The basking shark might be the rudest dinner guest in Canadian waters. In the summer, they swim into our Atlantic waters with their big mouth WIDE open to filter as much plankton as possible. As it gets colder, they take off and leave! We don’t even know where they’re going! That’s why we’re using a dart tagging program to better understand their movements and populations, so we can better track these big gluttons. Happy Shark Week, Canada!

status_message_cleaned: The first weeks of a Beluga whale's life are a transitional period during which the mother–calf bond is established. Since the calf's cries are still very faint, the mother may easily lose her baby if they wander too far from one another. This is why it’s important not to disturb these animals. In the presence of Beluga whales, keep your distance. status_message_cleaned: We’re deeply saddened by the loss of Campobello Whale Rescue eert Joe Howlett, who tragically lost his life while taking part in a rescue operation to disentangle a North Atlantic Right whale off the Eastern coast of New Brunswick. He was an eerienced and valued member of the whale rescue community. We are taking this incident very seriously and have paused all responses to entangled North Atlantic Right whales. While we are extremely concerned about the recent deaths and entanglements of these animals in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, it is imperative to review existing policies and practices regarding response to whale entanglements to ensure we proceed in the safest way possible for everyone involved. During this time, we continue to take action towards the recovery, protection and conservation of endangered whales. For more information on the work DFO and partners are doing, and for status updates on the North Atlantic Right whale situation in the Gulf, view our website:

status_message_cleaned: The Nunatsiavut Government, DFO in Newfoundland & Labrador and the Atlantic Salmon Federation are tagging salmon in Lake Melville, this summer.
